    <h1>LS Command in Terminal</h1>
    <p>The <code>ls</code> command is used to list files and directories in Unix-like operating systems such as Linux and macOS. It is commonly used in the terminal to view the contents of a directory.</p>

    <h2>Basic Syntax</h2>
    <pre>ls [options] [directory]</pre>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>[options]</strong> - Flags to modify the behavior of <code>ls</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>[directory]</strong> - The directory to list (if not specified, it lists the current directory).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Commonly Used Options</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>-l</strong> (long listing format): Displays detailed information such as file permissions, size, owner, and modification date.</li>
        <pre>ls -l</pre>
        <li><strong>-a</strong> (all): Lists all files, including hidden files (those starting with a dot <code>.</code>).</li>
        <pre>ls -a</pre>
        <li><strong>-h</strong> (human-readable): Displays file sizes in human-readable format (e.g., KB, MB).</li>
        <pre>ls -lh</pre>
        <li><strong>-R</strong> (recursive): Lists files and directories recursively, including files in subdirectories.</li>
        <pre>ls -R</pre>
        <li><strong>-S</strong> (sort by size): Sorts files by size, with the largest files listed first.</li>
        <pre>ls -S</pre>
        <li><strong>-t</strong> (sort by time): Sorts files by modification time, with the most recently modified files listed first.</li>
        <pre>ls -t</pre>
        <li><strong>-r</strong> (reverse): Reverses the order of the list, often used with sorting options.</li>
        <pre>ls -lr</pre>
        <li><strong>-1</strong> (one per line): Displays each file on a new line.</li>
        <pre>ls -1</pre>
        <li><strong>--color</strong>: Displays files with color-coding based on file type.</li>
        <pre>ls --color</pre>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example Usages</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Basic list</strong>
            <pre>ls</pre>
        </li>
        <li><strong>List with details</strong>
            <pre>ls -l</pre>
        </li>
        <li><strong>List all files (including hidden ones)</strong>
            <pre>ls -a</pre>
        </li>
        <li><strong>List files in long format with human-readable sizes</strong>
            <pre>ls -lh</pre>
        </li>
        <li><strong>List files in reverse time order</strong>
            <pre>ls -ltr</pre>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <p>The <code>ls</code> command is a versatile tool for listing and managing files in the terminal, and it's often used in conjunction with other commands like <code>git</code> for file management in repositories.</p>

